quran[7]{c,v,t}:
  11,6,"And there is no treading creature in the earth but its provision depends on Allah, and He knows its residence and its depository; all is in an evident record{1}.",footnotes:1:Literally ‘scripture’.
  11,7,"And it is He Who created the heavens and the earth in six days{1}—and His Throne was upon the waters—in order to test you as to which of you is better in conduct. And if you<sup>sg </sup>were to say, “You<sup>pl </sup>will be resurrected after death,” those who denied would most surely say, “This is nothing but evident sorcery{2}.”",footnotes:1:[Six equal intervals of time, which may be six heavenly days, each of them being 1000 earthly years long (see 22:47).],footnotes:2:[Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “…an evident sorcerer.”]
  11,8,"And if We were to defer the punishment from them until a fixed period of time, they would most surely say, “What holds it back?” Undoubtedly, on the day when it comes to them, it is not averted from them, and they became{1}surrounded by what they used to ridicule.",footnotes:1:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  11,9,"And if We were to give man a taste of mercy from Us and then withdraw it from him, he is very truly a constantly despairing, staunch denier."
  11,10,"And if We were to give him a taste of prosperity after some adversity has touched him, he would most surely say, “Troubles have gone away from me;” he is very truly exultant, boastful—"
